  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why can't India get more medals in Olympics?",
  "response": "India's performance in the Olympics has been a subject of discussion for many years. A few key factors that have historically contributed to the relatively lower medal counts for India include:\n\n1. **Infrastructure and Facilities**: For many years, India struggled with inadequate sports infrastructure and facilities, which affected athletes' training and performance. Although this is improving, there is still a need for more state-of-the-art facilities across various sports disciplines.\n\n2. **Funding and Support**: Insufficient funding for athletes, especially in sports other than cricket, has been a persistent issue. This includes not only direct financial support for athletes but also investment in coaching, physiotherapy, nutrition, and technical analysis.\n\n3. **Training and Coaching**: The quality of training and coaching available to Indian athletes has, at times, been below the standards set by top-performing countries. Access to world-class coaches is essential for competing at the highest levels.\n\n4. **Sports Culture and Awareness**: Cricket dominates the sports culture in India, and other sports often do not receive the same level of attention or encouragement. This can impact the perception of sports as a viable career path, leading to fewer participants in other disciplines.\n\n5. **Identification and Development of Talent**: There has been a need for better talent identification processes at the grassroots level and consistent development programs to nurture young athletes from an early age.\n\n6. **Socio-economic Factors**: Many talented athletes come from socio-economically disadvantaged backgrounds, and they face challenges related to access to resources and financial stability, which can hinder their progress.\n\n7. **Bureaucratic and Administrative Issues**: Sports administration in India has often been criticized for bureaucracy, lack of accountability, and inefficiencies, which can impede the development of athletes and sports programs.\n\n8. **Psychological and Mental Conditioning**: Competing at the international level requires not only physical preparedness but also strong mental conditioning. Focus on mental health and psychological training is sometimes lacking.\n\nDespite these challenges, India has been making significant strides in improving its performance in recent years, with increased investment, more focus on lesser-known sports, and better infrastructure and training programs. Various government schemes and private sponsorships are gradually creating an environment conducive to better performance on the world stage. The situation is evolving, and there is optimism that India will continue to improve its medal tally in future Olympics.",
